{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01NbdgXmLvk4Snr8tJqi3Hnm","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The `data` volume is an `emptyDir` - it's ephemeral per-pod. When a pod is deleted and recreated (during a rolling restart), the new pod gets a fresh emptyDir. So there's no persistent data.\n\nBut then why does the cluster UUID match? This might be because Elasticsearch re-joins the existing cluster with the same UUID (the cluster UUID is advertised by the master node), not because it's stored locally.\n\nOK, so the issue is:\n1. All 3 ES pods restarted\n2. They're starting fresh with no data since the volume is ephemeral\n3. They're re-bootstrapping the cluster and the `.security-7` index is being created\n\nThis should be a temporary state. Since `cluster.initial_master_nodes` only requires a quorum (2 out of 3 nodes), the cluster should be able to form even if not all nodes are up yet. Let me wait for it to stabilize.\n\nActually, I'm noticing the node IDs and cluster UUID are the same as before, which suggests the cluster might not have actually re-bootstrapped. When nodes restart with empty data directories, they should still be able to rejoin the existing cluster through the transport protocol. But wait—the cluster state is stored in the data directory itself. If that's empty, these are fresh nodes that need to bootstrap from scratch.\n\nThe key thing is that `cluster.initial_master_nodes` only applies to the initial cluster formation. Once a cluster exists, nodes use their stored state to rejoin, not this setting. If all 3 nodes lost their data simultaneously, they'd all be fresh nodes trying to bootstrap together.\n\nSo what's happening now: all three pods restarted with fresh emptyDir volumes, they're waiting for each other to form a new cluster, and once a master is elected, it'll initialize the security index using the bootstrap password from the environment variable. The `UnavailableShardsException` for the security index is expected during this bootstrap phase—the cluster is still forming and the index isn't ready yet. The readiness probes are failing because authentication can't work until the security index is available.\n\nI'm noticing something odd though: the cluster UUID in the current logs matches what it was before the restart. That shouldn't happen if the data was truly wiped. In a StatefulSet, when a pod is deleted and recreated, the new pod gets a fresh emptyDir, so the data should be gone. But the cluster UUID persisting suggests something else might be going on with how the cluster state is being preserved or recovered. the StatefulSet waits for each pod to become Ready before proceeding to the next one in the rolling restart sequence. The readiness probe checks the Elasticsearch password from the secret, but there's a mismatch—the secret now contains `elasticpass-elastic-password-next`, while the actual password stored in the cluster through the API might be different, which could be causing the readiness checks to fail. Let me trace through the pod status changes in the logs more carefully. elasticsearch-2 was Ready at lines 17-19 and again at lines 33-35, but then at lines 41-43 it suddenly dropped to `0/1`. That's strange—what caused elasticsearch-2 to become unready right after elasticsearch-0 came back online?\n\nI think when elasticsearch-0 rejoined the cluster, it triggered a shard rebalancing. elasticsearch-2 might have temporarily lost shards during this reallocation, causing the `.security-7` index to have unassigned shards. But here's the real issue: when elasticsearch-0 restarts with the `ELASTIC_PASSWORD` environment variable set, the Elasticsearch image might attempt to reset the bootstrap password, but that only works if the security index doesn't already have a stored password hash. If the cluster's `.security-7` index already contains the elastic user's hash, this could cause a conflict or authentication failure.\n\nLooking at the pod status progression, all three nodes dropped to 0/1 readiness around lines 45-47 and stayed stuck there, which suggests something went wrong during or after the rebalancing process.\n\nThe error logs point to the real issue: elasticsearch-0 restarted with empty data, which means it lost the primary shards for the `.security-7` index that were stored locally. When the cluster tried to reassign those shards to other nodes, the security index became unavailable across the board, and without access to the security index, no node could authenticate users anymore—creating a cascading failure where all three nodes became unready. elasticsearch-2's replicas were lost too. So during the rolling restart, when elasticsearch-2 went down first, elasticsearch-0 and elasticsearch-1 should've kept the data alive—but then they also restarted and lost their copies. Without persistent volumes, all the `.security-7` shard data across the entire cluster disappeared, forcing it to rebuild from nothing. I'm realizing the replica shards might also get wiped during their restarts, but then they resync from the primary. When elasticsearch-2 restarted, it lost its replica data but rejoined and synced from the primary on elasticsearch-0. The same happened with elasticsearch-1, which synced the updated security data from the master. But the real problem emerges when elasticsearch-0 finally restarts—if both -1 and -2 have replica copies of the shards that were primary on -0, those replicas can be promoted to primary, potentially causing data loss if they're out of sync.\n\nActually, I think the core issue is how Elasticsearch handles empty local data on restart. When a node loses its data and rejoins, it needs to perform a full reset and resync all shards from the primary, which is tracked in the cluster state. So when elasticsearch-1 restarted and synced from elasticsearch-0, then elasticsearch-0 itself restarts with empty data, it becomes a fresh node that needs shard assignment. The problem is whether the cluster recognizes it as the same node (based on stored node.id) or treats it as completely new, which affects how it rejoins and whether it can authenticate during the rebalancing process. ID `YYg4-8NRT5G1LAoaARKcaQ`. The cluster can't reconcile these mismatched node IDs, which is a fundamental problem when using emptyDir storage without persistence.\n\nThe real issue is that the rolling restart wiped all three nodes' data, giving them new IDs and leaving the cluster in an inconsistent state where the security index shards can't be located. I think the fix is to delete all three pods at once to force a complete fresh bootstrap, then let them form a new cluster using the ELASTIC_PASSWORD environment variable.\n\nOnce they restart with the updated secret value, everything should align—the ES nodes will have the new password set during initialization, the readiness probes will authenticate with that same password, and the auth-checker will also use the matching credentials from the secret. But I need to think through whether deleting all three pods simultaneously will cause the StatefulSet to handle the recreation properly. The data directories might be inconsistent with a mix of stale and fresh emptyDir data, or there could be a quorum issue preventing master election. Let me try checking if Elasticsearch can authenticate at all before proceeding with the pod deletion.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1473,"cache_read_input_tokens":59825,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1473},"output_tokens":27,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"0cd4ff8e-42d6-47ed-8f89-a407d46a89b3","uuid":"4aacfcd9-e5e3-4eac-84e0-67da752f34f0","request_id":"req_011CcPAVbWGyBGL4SwqDZPXg"}
